1
00:00:11,440 --> 00:00:13,000
First we have a note.

2
00:00:15,720 --> 00:00:17,200
Then we have a tune.

3
00:00:24,080 --> 00:00:26,280
Then we have a melody.

4
00:00:30,920 --> 00:00:34,400
Beethoven wrote this when
he first discovered he was going deaf.

5
00:00:35,640 --> 00:00:38,720
All that rage and fury,

6
00:00:39,560 --> 00:00:42,840
out of which, something beautiful.

7
00:00:44,760 --> 00:00:46,320
Am I boring you, Henry?

8
00:00:46,320 --> 00:00:48,800
- It's just a bit stuffy.

9
00:00:48,800 --> 00:00:50,400
Can't you play
something more exciting, sir?

10
00:00:50,400 --> 00:00:53,080
There is one thing you might like.

11
00:00:53,080 --> 00:00:54,560
It's called the Devil's chord.

12
00:00:54,560 --> 00:00:55,680
Tell me more, sir.

13
00:00:55,680 --> 00:00:58,520
It was banned by the church
in medieval times

14
00:00:58,520 --> 00:01:01,080
in case it allows
the Devil to enter the room.

15
00:01:05,240 --> 00:01:07,760
Makes you shiver, doesn't it?

16
00:01:07,760 --> 00:01:09,680
Technically, it's known as a tritone,

17
00:01:09,680 --> 00:01:12,600
but, uh, put it in context and, uh...

18
00:01:24,880 --> 00:01:26,200
Oh! Gosh.

19
00:01:26,200 --> 00:01:27,400
Oh, goodness me. Uh--

20
00:01:29,200 --> 00:01:30,200
What?

21
00:01:33,360 --> 00:01:34,720
Is someone playing a game?

22
00:01:41,640 --> 00:01:43,720
Ta-da!

23
00:01:48,880 --> 00:01:50,800
- Henry, get away from him.
Them.

24
00:01:50,800 --> 00:01:52,080
What?
- Me.

25
00:01:52,080 --> 00:01:53,600
What?
- I'm them.

26
00:01:53,600 --> 00:01:55,840
- You're who?
-"You're who?"

27
00:01:55,840 --> 00:01:59,240
Nice to see you again, kiddo.

28
00:01:59,240 --> 00:02:01,040
- You know each other?

29
00:02:01,040 --> 00:02:02,440
That's my daddy.

30
00:02:02,440 --> 00:02:03,600
Don't be ridiculous.

31
00:02:03,600 --> 00:02:05,120
You didn't look at my name, sir.

32
00:02:05,720 --> 00:02:07,080
Course I did.

33
00:02:07,080 --> 00:02:09,160
It's Henry-- What was it? Henry...

34
00:02:10,240 --> 00:02:11,920
"Henry Arbinger". That's it.

35
00:02:15,560 --> 00:02:17,640
Harbinger.

36
00:02:19,520 --> 00:02:22,160
Think of him as my prelude.

37
00:02:22,160 --> 00:02:26,080
And now his song is sung.

38
00:02:27,480 --> 00:02:28,840
Wh-- Who are you?

39
00:02:28,840 --> 00:02:33,640
My notation is Maestro.

40
00:02:33,640 --> 00:02:35,640
But what are you?

41
00:02:35,640 --> 00:02:38,480
I am...

42
00:02:39,840 --> 00:02:41,880
music.

43
00:02:43,800 --> 00:02:49,000
And you, Mr Timothy Drake,
you're a genius.

44
00:02:49,600 --> 00:02:51,080
Don't be ridiculous.

45
00:02:51,080 --> 00:02:55,920
You're the greatest composer
who ever lived.

46
00:02:57,160 --> 00:02:59,800
Clever enough to find the lost chord.

47
00:02:59,800 --> 00:03:04,680
But it's so sad, Timothy.

48
00:03:05,760 --> 00:03:07,720
You never had the luck.

49
00:03:08,320 --> 00:03:11,600
You never got that break.

50
00:03:12,200 --> 00:03:13,200
I did not.

51
00:03:13,200 --> 00:03:15,800
You're right.
No-Nobody ever understood me.

52
00:03:15,800 --> 00:03:22,640
All those melodies,
stifled and strangled inside you.

53
00:03:23,920 --> 00:03:30,480
All those songs you never sang,
they sit there still,

54
00:03:31,200 --> 00:03:38,000
wrapped around your heart, still beating.

55
00:03:38,760 --> 00:03:45,240
Wrapped so tight.

56
00:03:47,920 --> 00:03:50,560
Would you like me to set them free?

57
00:03:51,160 --> 00:03:53,800
I would love that, yes. Yes.

58
00:03:54,960 --> 00:03:59,480
Music, Maestro, please.

59
00:04:40,640 --> 00:04:41,880
Now.

60
00:05:30,200 --> 00:05:31,680
I wanna see

61
00:05:32,400 --> 00:05:37,880
The Beatles
recording their very first album.

62
00:05:41,680 --> 00:05:43,320
- Seriously?
- Well, you asked.

63
00:05:43,320 --> 00:05:45,120
If I could go anywhere in time and space,

64
00:05:45,120 --> 00:05:47,920
that's where I'd go because my mum,
she had a girlfriend, Claire.

65
00:05:47,920 --> 00:05:50,320
And I loved Claire,
and she was dead into vinyl.

66
00:05:50,320 --> 00:05:53,760
She had all The Beatles albums, so we
used to play 'em every day after school.

67
00:05:53,760 --> 00:05:55,160
Ten years old, I was.

68
00:05:55,160 --> 00:05:57,040
We had Revolver, the White Album--

69
00:05:57,040 --> 00:05:59,880
So, yeah, if I could go anywhere
then that's where I'd go.

70
00:06:03,360 --> 00:06:07,920
That is amazing.

71
00:06:07,920 --> 00:06:09,840
- Oh! Wait, seriously?
- Oh!

72
00:06:09,840 --> 00:06:11,760
- People always say the Titanic.

73
00:06:11,760 --> 00:06:13,720
- Or Mars. Or Bethlehem.
- Oh!

74
00:06:13,720 --> 00:06:15,880
- But The Beatles!

75
00:06:15,880 --> 00:06:18,280
- Why have I never done that before?

76
00:06:18,280 --> 00:06:19,760
- Come on!
- Oh!

77
00:06:21,280 --> 00:06:22,640
- Oh.

78
00:06:23,680 --> 00:06:25,720
February 11th, 1963.

79
00:06:25,720 --> 00:06:27,280
No way. Really?
- Mm-hmm.

80
00:06:27,280 --> 00:06:29,600
Whoo!

81
00:06:29,600 --> 00:06:31,040
Oh, wait, wait, wait.

82
00:06:31,040 --> 00:06:34,880
If we're in the '60s,
what about my clothes?

83
00:06:37,160 --> 00:06:38,880
Good thinking.

84
00:06:38,880 --> 00:06:40,560
Could give you go-go boots.

85
00:06:40,560 --> 00:06:42,640
Oh, I've got eyeliner!
- Oh, eyeliner!

86
00:06:42,640 --> 00:06:45,600
Oh, I want a beehive! I want a beehive!

87
00:06:45,600 --> 00:06:47,560
I've got wigs galore!

88
00:06:49,200 --> 00:06:51,720
♪ Like a sound you hear
That lingers in your ear ♪

89
00:06:51,720 --> 00:06:57,520
♪ But you can't forget
From sundown to sunset, now, now ♪

90
00:06:59,360 --> 00:07:01,760
♪ It's all in the air
You hear it everywhere ♪

91
00:07:01,760 --> 00:07:06,960
♪ No matter what you do
It's gonna grab a hold on you ♪

92
00:07:07,960 --> 00:07:11,120
♪ California soul ♪

93
00:07:13,280 --> 00:07:16,040
1963.

94
00:07:16,040 --> 00:07:18,080
Hey, hey, hey!

95
00:07:18,080 --> 00:07:19,440
- Oh, no way!

96
00:07:19,440 --> 00:07:21,560
It's like the album cover!

97
00:07:21,560 --> 00:07:23,560
I am having the best time!

98
00:07:23,560 --> 00:07:25,760
Look at the cars.
- G-- Oh, come on!

99
00:07:35,520 --> 00:07:37,840
- Abbey Road Studios!

100
00:07:37,840 --> 00:07:39,440
Not called Abbey Road yet.

101
00:07:39,440 --> 00:07:45,280
Right now, in '63,
they are the EMI Recording Studios.

102
00:07:45,280 --> 00:07:47,480
Huh.

103
00:07:49,480 --> 00:07:51,240
And how do we get in?

104
00:07:51,240 --> 00:07:53,560
- Won't they ask who we are?

105
00:07:53,560 --> 00:07:55,240
Oh! Oh, oh, oh, oh.

106
00:07:55,240 --> 00:07:57,000
Hi.

107
00:07:57,000 --> 00:07:59,520
Janet said we could take over,
so you can have ten minutes off.

108
00:07:59,520 --> 00:08:03,280
Oh, right. Thank you. Very kind.

109
00:08:04,560 --> 00:08:08,160
Yep. There's always a Janet.
And everyone wants a cuppa.

110
00:08:08,160 --> 00:08:11,080
- Brilliant.

111
00:08:15,000 --> 00:08:16,360
Good morning.

112
00:08:16,360 --> 00:08:17,440
Cuppa tea?

113
00:08:18,160 --> 00:08:21,320
Uh, yeah.
Make it a strong one. Two sugars.

114
00:08:21,320 --> 00:08:22,840
- Uh.

115
00:08:22,840 --> 00:08:24,080
Boys, do you want anything?

116
00:08:24,080 --> 00:08:27,000
I'm all right for now.
Maybe something stronger later on.

117
00:08:27,000 --> 00:08:29,040
- What do you think, John?
- Now you're talking, Paul, lad.

118
00:08:29,040 --> 00:08:30,720
I just want a good night's sleep.

119
00:08:30,720 --> 00:08:33,720
You keep playing like that,
we'll all have a good kip.

120
00:08:33,720 --> 00:08:35,600
All right. Let's take it from the top.

121
00:08:35,600 --> 00:08:38,000
I thought the chorus--
Don't slide in the harmonies. Just hit it.

122
00:08:38,000 --> 00:08:39,320
Whatever you say, boss.

123
00:08:39,320 --> 00:08:42,640
Hurry up then, George.
Only getting paid seven quid a day.

124
00:08:42,640 --> 00:08:45,040
Uh, good luck.
Thanks, love.

125
00:08:47,720 --> 00:08:49,440
Roll to record.

126
00:08:49,440 --> 00:08:51,760
And a three, two, one.

127
00:08:51,760 --> 00:08:53,160
♪ I've got a dog ♪

128
00:08:53,160 --> 00:08:54,440
♪ He's called Fred ♪

129
00:08:54,440 --> 00:08:56,120
♪ My dog is alive ♪

130
00:08:56,120 --> 00:08:57,480
♪ He's not dead ♪

131
00:08:57,480 --> 00:08:59,160
♪ I love my dog ♪

132
00:08:59,160 --> 00:09:00,760
♪ He loves me too ♪

133
00:09:00,760 --> 00:09:02,280
♪ I haven't got a cat ♪

134
00:09:02,280 --> 00:09:03,600
♪ Only a dog ♪

135
00:09:03,600 --> 00:09:06,680
♪ My dog, my dog, my dog, my dog ♪

136
00:09:06,680 --> 00:09:08,240
♪ I've got a dog ♪

137
00:09:08,240 --> 00:09:09,720
♪ I love my dog ♪

138
00:09:09,720 --> 00:09:10,800
♪ He's my dog ♪

139
00:09:10,800 --> 00:09:12,440
♪ He's not your dog ♪

140
00:09:12,440 --> 00:09:15,480
♪ If you want a dog
Get your own ♪

141
00:09:24,320 --> 00:09:26,560
Hi. Don't mind us.
Just a cuppa tea.

142
00:09:26,560 --> 00:09:27,640
Okay.

143
00:09:28,520 --> 00:09:30,200
Going from the second chorus.

144
00:09:30,200 --> 00:09:32,280
Playing in the last four bars
of the verse.

145
00:09:32,280 --> 00:09:33,720
Good luck, Cilla.

146
00:09:33,720 --> 00:09:35,080
Don't let me down, Cilla.

147
00:09:35,080 --> 00:09:36,880
And a three, two, one.

148
00:09:36,880 --> 00:09:38,480
♪ I love you ♪

149
00:09:38,480 --> 00:09:40,040
♪ You love me ♪

150
00:09:40,040 --> 00:09:41,640
♪ We are two ♪

151
00:09:41,640 --> 00:09:44,000
♪ We are not three ♪

152
00:09:44,000 --> 00:09:46,120
♪ 'Cause you love me ♪

153
00:09:46,120 --> 00:09:48,960
♪ And I love you ♪

154
00:09:48,960 --> 00:09:50,320
♪ We're quite happy ♪

155
00:09:50,320 --> 00:09:51,400
♪ I think ♪

156
00:09:51,400 --> 00:09:53,480
♪ Perhaps ♪

157
00:09:54,840 --> 00:09:56,720
Oh, Cilla.

158
00:10:00,280 --> 00:10:01,280
Don't mind us.

159
00:10:02,520 --> 00:10:05,080
Roll to record.

160
00:10:20,640 --> 00:10:21,640
Look at them.

161
00:10:23,520 --> 00:10:25,040
Everything's gone dull.

162
00:10:25,960 --> 00:10:28,520
No one hums. No one whistles.

163
00:10:28,520 --> 00:10:30,000
No one taps their feet.

164
00:10:30,000 --> 00:10:31,440
I don't get it though.

165
00:10:32,200 --> 00:10:33,200
Music isn't...

166
00:10:34,280 --> 00:10:36,640
Like, you can't lose it
or steal it or kill it.

167
00:10:36,640 --> 00:10:37,720
It's just natural.

168
00:10:37,720 --> 00:10:40,800
You get music
when the wind blows through the trees.

169
00:10:40,800 --> 00:10:42,560
It's called aeolian tones.

170
00:10:43,080 --> 00:10:44,080
The music--

171
00:10:44,080 --> 00:10:48,280
Music is the highest form of thought.
If you take that away...

172
00:10:49,200 --> 00:10:51,320
Finland? That never happened.

173
00:10:54,000 --> 00:10:56,600
If music is gone,
that means everything is changing.

174
00:10:57,200 --> 00:10:59,560
The whole human race
is taking a different path.

175
00:10:59,560 --> 00:11:01,240
Okay, so what do we do?

176
00:11:01,240 --> 00:11:03,320
You take John Lennon.
I'll take Paul McCartney.

177
00:11:03,320 --> 00:11:05,760
Find out what happened
and when it happened.

178
00:11:07,120 --> 00:11:09,280
- Two cups of tea, my darlings.

179
00:11:09,280 --> 00:11:11,160
That's half a crown. Ta very much.

180
00:11:11,160 --> 00:11:12,640
How much?

181
00:11:12,640 --> 00:11:14,400
- That is outrageous.
- Outrageous.

182
00:11:14,400 --> 00:11:15,840
Take it or leave it, sweetheart.

183
00:11:15,840 --> 00:11:18,440
That is daylight robbery.

184
00:11:18,440 --> 00:11:23,200
Ooh. That's me.
Margaret Lockwood in The Wicked Lady.

185
00:11:23,200 --> 00:11:24,800
Now there was a woman.

186
00:11:25,480 --> 00:11:26,760
Statuesque.

187
00:11:26,760 --> 00:11:28,440
Uh, excuse me. Hold on, Paul.

188
00:11:28,440 --> 00:11:30,800
Um, could I just have a word?

189
00:11:30,800 --> 00:11:33,560
I've got a cup of tea for you.
Mr Epstein sent me.

190
00:11:34,760 --> 00:11:36,520
Okay. Um--

191
00:11:36,520 --> 00:11:39,560
Y-You are writing songs
for the band, yeah?

192
00:11:40,320 --> 00:11:41,720
They're not very good, are they?

193
00:11:41,720 --> 00:11:43,360
Oh. Uh.

194
00:11:44,720 --> 00:11:46,440
No. No.

195
00:11:46,440 --> 00:11:47,520
Great.

196
00:11:48,360 --> 00:11:50,200
That's great, lad.
That's how it should be.

197
00:11:50,720 --> 00:11:53,720
It's not like the old days when we had
waltzes and fandangoes and all that.

198
00:11:53,720 --> 00:11:55,680
But waltzes used to exist.

199
00:11:55,680 --> 00:11:57,560
When did they start becoming wrong?

200
00:11:58,360 --> 00:12:01,280
Don't know. Way back. '20s? '30s?

201
00:12:01,280 --> 00:12:03,200
Why? What happened?

202
00:12:04,320 --> 00:12:05,920
We started seeing sense.

203
00:12:07,000 --> 00:12:09,320
What we're doing here today
is the last gasp.

204
00:12:10,160 --> 00:12:12,200
If I can make a bit of money
out of cheap, old rhymes,

205
00:12:12,200 --> 00:12:14,400
then I can settle down
and get a proper job.

206
00:12:14,400 --> 00:12:17,280
It's embarrassing, singing.

207
00:12:17,280 --> 00:12:21,040
Just wanna finish the album, get back
to Liverpool and... [sighs] ...forget it.

208
00:12:21,640 --> 00:12:22,920
But you can't do that.

209
00:12:22,920 --> 00:12:24,760
Wh-- [chuckles] We need ya.

210
00:12:24,760 --> 00:12:27,400
What for? I'm no good at anything.

211
00:12:29,200 --> 00:12:30,400
But, Paul,

212
00:12:30,920 --> 00:12:33,160
see when it's just you on your own,

213
00:12:34,000 --> 00:12:38,600
don't you think
that there must be better songs?

214
00:12:38,600 --> 00:12:41,840
You know, songs that lift you

215
00:12:41,840 --> 00:12:45,320
and devastate you and-and make you soar.

216
00:12:46,120 --> 00:12:51,840
Songs that are-are tucked away somewhere
in-in secret in the back of your mind?

217
00:12:56,040 --> 00:12:57,680
How do you know that?

218
00:12:58,400 --> 00:13:00,200
I-- I just wanna go home.

219
00:13:02,720 --> 00:13:04,040
Forget this life.

220
00:13:05,800 --> 00:13:08,760
Just have me tea and go to bed
with a woman of me own, you know?

221
00:13:10,240 --> 00:13:11,400
It's all I want.

222
00:13:18,120 --> 00:13:20,080
But then, why do I wake up crying?

223
00:13:20,800 --> 00:13:24,440
It's like, sometimes, late at night,
I get this thought.

224
00:13:25,200 --> 00:13:29,800
Like, it's so far away, but it's a note.

225
00:13:30,680 --> 00:13:31,960
A single note.

226
00:13:33,120 --> 00:13:34,360
And then a second.

227
00:13:34,880 --> 00:13:37,720
And a third and fourth and fifth.

228
00:13:38,760 --> 00:13:43,600
And you put them together, and it feels
like the most holy thing on this earth.

229
00:13:45,520 --> 00:13:50,000
Like a G, then an E.

230
00:13:51,480 --> 00:13:53,040
And a G, maybe twice.

231
00:13:54,640 --> 00:13:55,640
And then C.

232
00:13:59,400 --> 00:14:03,000
And if you put words to it,
words right from your heart...

233
00:14:05,080 --> 00:14:10,560
♪ I love you so much ♪

234
00:14:45,160 --> 00:14:46,640
Don't waste me time.

235
00:14:48,560 --> 00:14:50,560
Do you know what you are
with your ideas, pal?

236
00:14:50,560 --> 00:14:53,240
Disgusting. You are disgusting.

237
00:14:58,880 --> 00:15:02,200
What the hell was that?

238
00:15:03,440 --> 00:15:05,280
Yeah, that's it, Vinnie. Nice and safe.

239
00:15:05,280 --> 00:15:08,560
I want that installed on the rooftop
like it is precious china.

240
00:15:08,560 --> 00:15:11,040
Easy, boys. Don't hit the wall.

241
00:15:11,040 --> 00:15:13,280
Right, let's head on up.

242
00:15:15,120 --> 00:15:19,200
Thing is, without music,
dance must be gone.

243
00:15:19,200 --> 00:15:20,800
No one dances anymore.

244
00:15:20,800 --> 00:15:22,320
I mean, can you dance without music?

245
00:15:22,320 --> 00:15:24,160
I mean, you can, but do you want to?

246
00:15:24,160 --> 00:15:25,760
And think about it, Ruby. Love songs.

247
00:15:25,760 --> 00:15:27,560
There are no more love songs anymore.

248
00:15:27,560 --> 00:15:28,640
Oh, my God!

249
00:15:28,640 --> 00:15:31,480
There's no more love songs
in the whole wide world.

250
00:15:33,200 --> 00:15:34,520
- Ooh.

251
00:15:34,520 --> 00:15:36,080
Old London Town!

252
00:15:36,080 --> 00:15:37,200
- Oh, is that smog?

253
00:15:37,200 --> 00:15:38,880
I thought they got rid of that
in the '50s.

254
00:15:38,880 --> 00:15:43,080
We had really bad smog
in December '62, but this?

255
00:15:43,720 --> 00:15:45,280
It's more like a darkening.

256
00:15:46,040 --> 00:15:47,840
The world is darkening.

257
00:15:47,840 --> 00:15:50,200
I live over there.

258
00:15:50,200 --> 00:15:51,960
You do what?
- I live over there.

259
00:15:51,960 --> 00:15:53,520
- What do you mean?
- Shoreditch.

260
00:15:53,520 --> 00:15:54,680
I'm there right now.

261
00:15:54,680 --> 00:15:56,480
Okay, you're gonna have to start again.

262
00:15:56,480 --> 00:15:59,720
In the past, right now,
I live in a place called Totter's Lane.

263
00:16:00,520 --> 00:16:03,040
1963, I parked the TARDIS in a junkyard,

264
00:16:03,040 --> 00:16:04,920
and I live there
with my granddaughter, Susan.

265
00:16:04,920 --> 00:16:06,600
- Ah. Wh--

266
00:16:07,160 --> 00:16:09,200
- Okay?
- Your what?

267
00:16:09,200 --> 00:16:10,440
- My granddaughter.
- Susan?

268
00:16:10,440 --> 00:16:13,480
We could go and have a look but,
you know, timelines.

269
00:16:13,480 --> 00:16:15,720
- Wh-- You-You've got children?
- I did have.

270
00:16:15,720 --> 00:16:17,120
I will have.

271
00:16:17,120 --> 00:16:19,200
Time Lords get a bit complicated.

272
00:16:19,200 --> 00:16:20,720
Yeah, but you've got a granddaughter?

273
00:16:20,720 --> 00:16:23,240
Like, now? Like, today?
Back in our time? My time.

274
00:16:23,240 --> 00:16:25,400
Where is she?
- I don't know.

275
00:16:27,320 --> 00:16:29,080
How do you not know?

276
00:16:29,080 --> 00:16:30,640
The Time Lords were murdered.

277
00:16:31,160 --> 00:16:34,520
Genocide rolled across time and space
like a great, big cellular explosion.

278
00:16:34,520 --> 00:16:35,680
Maybe it killed her too.

279
00:16:35,680 --> 00:16:37,520
Doctor. God.

280
00:16:45,440 --> 00:16:46,440
There we go, Doc.

281
00:16:46,440 --> 00:16:48,520
- Hey, Vinnie!

282
00:16:48,520 --> 00:16:49,800
Thank you very much.

283
00:16:50,520 --> 00:16:51,520
Come on.

284
00:16:51,520 --> 00:16:54,000
Bit of luck,
I'll have you whistling by sundown.

285
00:16:54,000 --> 00:16:58,040
Can't bear whistling, Doc.
All those horrible tunes. No, thanks!

286
00:16:58,040 --> 00:16:59,240
Well, all right.

287
00:17:06,680 --> 00:17:08,360
It's all yours, honey.

288
00:17:08,360 --> 00:17:10,840
Oh, no, no, no, no, no. I'm--

289
00:17:10,840 --> 00:17:12,320
I'm not that good.

290
00:17:12,320 --> 00:17:15,200
Uh, you are, sweet. I've seen you.

291
00:17:15,200 --> 00:17:17,240
December '23. King's Arms.

292
00:17:17,240 --> 00:17:18,840
You opened with "One More Sleep"?

293
00:17:22,120 --> 00:17:23,520
Oh, I can't believe you were there.

294
00:17:23,520 --> 00:17:26,520
Ah. It all comes back to Christmas
with you, doesn't it?

295
00:17:26,520 --> 00:17:28,480
I need you to play again.

296
00:17:30,240 --> 00:17:31,240
But what for?

297
00:17:31,240 --> 00:17:34,440
At this moment in time, Ruby Sunday,
you are the only music in the world.

298
00:17:34,440 --> 00:17:37,240
Let's see what happens
if you bring music back.

299
00:17:38,400 --> 00:17:41,040
It's just-- No pressure.

300
00:17:43,480 --> 00:17:44,480
Okay.

301
00:17:45,320 --> 00:17:50,280
I wrote this for my friend Trudy
when a girl broke her heart.

302
00:17:50,280 --> 00:17:51,400
Mmm.

303
00:19:39,800 --> 00:19:41,080
Mmm.

304
00:20:01,680 --> 00:20:03,080
No!

305
00:20:04,320 --> 00:20:05,680
No!

306
00:20:29,800 --> 00:20:31,720
You called?

307
00:20:33,760 --> 00:20:35,320
That was the Giggle!

308
00:20:39,240 --> 00:20:41,120
- Hide!
Uh, do what?

309
00:20:41,120 --> 00:20:42,360
We've gotta hide!

310
00:20:42,360 --> 00:20:43,520
You never hide!

311
00:20:45,800 --> 00:20:48,200
I can't fight this thing.

312
00:20:48,200 --> 00:20:50,960
Okay.

313
00:20:56,680 --> 00:20:59,840
I heard music!

314
00:21:17,800 --> 00:21:23,640
♪ Where are you? ♪

315
00:21:26,360 --> 00:21:30,480
- Who was playing that piano?

316
00:21:31,640 --> 00:21:36,760
The chorus of ancient songs calls me...

317
00:21:36,760 --> 00:21:40,560
...Maestro.

318
00:21:40,560 --> 00:21:42,760
And who...

319
00:21:45,040 --> 00:21:47,240
...are you?

320
00:21:48,000 --> 00:21:51,760
Because I heard music.

321
00:21:54,840 --> 00:21:56,880
And music...

322
00:21:58,920 --> 00:22:02,280
...is mine!

323
00:22:21,440 --> 00:22:22,520
What?

324
00:22:24,880 --> 00:22:26,160
What?

325
00:23:19,120 --> 00:23:22,080
Sound and vision.

326
00:23:40,160 --> 00:23:42,200
Music.

327
00:24:08,680 --> 00:24:10,640
Wh-Who was that?
Were they inside the piano?

328
00:24:10,640 --> 00:24:12,320
- How can they be inside the piano?
- Okay.

329
00:24:12,320 --> 00:24:15,120
- The piano wouldn't work.
- Okay. Okay, okay, okay.

330
00:24:15,120 --> 00:24:16,200
Okay.

331
00:24:18,720 --> 00:24:19,920
You're scaring me now.

332
00:24:21,160 --> 00:24:25,080
That thing must be part of the Pantheon.

333
00:24:25,960 --> 00:24:27,840
Oh, God.

334
00:24:28,920 --> 00:24:31,040
Oh, Ruby, there are...

335
00:24:34,160 --> 00:24:38,480
vast powers beyond the universe.

336
00:24:39,400 --> 00:24:42,360
I told you, when we first met,
I said-I said, "The Toymaker",

337
00:24:42,360 --> 00:24:45,640
and defeating him took everything.

338
00:24:46,160 --> 00:24:48,120
- It ripped me in half.
- But you survived.

339
00:24:48,120 --> 00:24:50,960
It literally-- It tore my soul in half.

340
00:24:50,960 --> 00:24:53,520
I can't survive that again.

341
00:25:05,680 --> 00:25:09,680
The Toy-- The Toymaker said-- He said--

342
00:25:10,880 --> 00:25:11,880
He warned me.

343
00:25:11,880 --> 00:25:14,800
He said, "My legions are coming."

344
00:25:15,520 --> 00:25:16,680
"My legions are coming."

345
00:25:16,680 --> 00:25:19,720
- He said, "My legions are coming."
- But you made that silence with the sonic.

346
00:25:19,720 --> 00:25:20,960
- That worked, didn't it?
- Yeah.

347
00:25:20,960 --> 00:25:23,720
One trick. Once. That's all you get
with the gods.

348
00:25:23,720 --> 00:25:25,760
- Okay, so what do we do?
- I don't know.

349
00:25:25,760 --> 00:25:27,600
I don't know, Ruby. That is the point.

350
00:25:27,600 --> 00:25:29,760
- I don't know. I--
- No, but you always know.

351
00:25:29,760 --> 00:25:31,560
- I don't.

352
00:25:31,560 --> 00:25:34,040
The last time, I got lucky. Catch.

353
00:25:34,040 --> 00:25:35,800
One trick. Once.

354
00:25:36,760 --> 00:25:39,720
But this thing is stealing music.

355
00:25:39,720 --> 00:25:41,080
I mean, how the--

356
00:25:41,080 --> 00:25:42,600
How the hell is--

357
00:25:46,520 --> 00:25:48,000
- I'm sorry.

358
00:25:50,240 --> 00:25:53,040
But the power of these creatures
is so vast,

359
00:25:53,880 --> 00:25:56,280
the whole world could slide into the pit.

360
00:25:58,680 --> 00:25:59,680
Doctor.

361
00:26:01,920 --> 00:26:03,000
I know you're clever.

362
00:26:03,720 --> 00:26:04,880
I know that.

363
00:26:05,480 --> 00:26:06,960
But I've got news for ya.

364
00:26:08,280 --> 00:26:12,360
The world did not end in 1963.

365
00:26:13,320 --> 00:26:15,040
- Right.
- No, but it didn't.

366
00:26:15,040 --> 00:26:17,080
Okay? I'm living proof.

367
00:26:17,080 --> 00:26:18,840
- I was born in 2004...

368
00:26:18,840 --> 00:26:21,640
...and all my life,
I've had Beyoncé and Sam Fender

369
00:26:21,640 --> 00:26:25,000
and Strictly and tap dancing
and raves and--

370
00:26:25,000 --> 00:26:28,440
Oh, my mum sings "Danny Boy" at Christmas,
when she's drunk, to my gran.

371
00:26:28,440 --> 00:26:30,880
- And don't you see, Doctor?

372
00:26:32,160 --> 00:26:34,600
Music exists.

373
00:26:39,320 --> 00:26:40,520
Come with me.

374
00:26:45,640 --> 00:26:47,320
So when is it for you, back home?

375
00:26:47,320 --> 00:26:48,560
What time are you?

376
00:26:48,560 --> 00:26:49,920
June 2024?

377
00:26:49,920 --> 00:26:51,680
Uh, it's hard to keep track.

378
00:26:51,680 --> 00:26:52,880
But, yeah, I think so.

379
00:26:52,880 --> 00:26:54,560
- June? July?

380
00:27:00,960 --> 00:27:02,680
Well, have we done it? Are we back?

381
00:27:02,680 --> 00:27:04,520
2024. I've brought you home.

382
00:27:48,000 --> 00:27:49,640
This is what we're trying to stop.

383
00:27:54,240 --> 00:27:56,960
But this isn't real.

384
00:27:56,960 --> 00:27:58,680
This is--

385
00:27:58,680 --> 00:28:01,440
- It's just like a parallel universe.
- This is your time.

386
00:28:02,560 --> 00:28:05,800
This is your home
if Maestro isn't stopped.

387
00:28:12,560 --> 00:28:13,920
Where's my mum?

388
00:28:21,640 --> 00:28:25,800
I think without music,
the human race goes sour.

389
00:28:26,720 --> 00:28:28,760
Without any way of expressing
a broken heart,

390
00:28:28,760 --> 00:28:31,000
they go to war, without even knowing why.

391
00:28:35,640 --> 00:28:37,400
Then how am I still alive?

392
00:28:40,880 --> 00:28:42,480
Why don't I fade away?

393
00:28:42,480 --> 00:28:43,840
Because of me.

394
00:28:58,840 --> 00:28:59,920
- Boo!
What?

395
00:29:14,880 --> 00:29:18,240
Maestro, the Doctor.

396
00:29:19,560 --> 00:29:22,360
That was you in '63, wasn't it?

397
00:29:22,360 --> 00:29:24,720
Sweet cheeks.

398
00:29:24,720 --> 00:29:28,920
You stepped from one time to another...

399
00:29:30,000 --> 00:29:32,440
...like the Lord Temporal,

400
00:29:33,200 --> 00:29:37,800
who trapped my father
and bound him in salt.

401
00:29:37,800 --> 00:29:39,680
- Yes?
- The child of the Toymaker?

402
00:29:44,160 --> 00:29:47,040
I should thank you, Doctor.

403
00:29:47,040 --> 00:29:51,360
Daddy was so bad to me.

404
00:29:54,360 --> 00:29:56,640
♪ Daddy was so mean ♪

405
00:29:56,640 --> 00:29:58,320
♪ Daddy was so tough ♪

406
00:29:58,320 --> 00:29:59,960
♪ Daddy daddied me ♪

407
00:29:59,960 --> 00:30:01,400
♪ And that was quite enough ♪

408
00:30:02,320 --> 00:30:06,160
If he was a living game,
you are the essence of music itself?

409
00:30:08,040 --> 00:30:11,320
But what's the point?
You've destroyed the world.

410
00:30:11,320 --> 00:30:15,000
Music is gone. How is that a win?

411
00:30:15,000 --> 00:30:17,440
Not gone!

412
00:30:17,440 --> 00:30:19,920
Darling, hush!

413
00:30:28,960 --> 00:30:33,920
The sound of a nuclear winter.

414
00:30:34,960 --> 00:30:37,880
The purest music of all.

415
00:30:38,480 --> 00:30:40,000
Aeolian tones.

416
00:30:40,000 --> 00:30:42,160
Music without the need of people.

417
00:30:42,920 --> 00:30:48,600
And every song that goes unsung feeds me.

418
00:30:48,600 --> 00:30:51,880
I get stronger and stronger.

419
00:30:51,880 --> 00:30:54,720
Until I can reach out...

420
00:30:54,720 --> 00:30:58,120
...and steal the music of the spheres.

421
00:30:59,480 --> 00:31:02,960
Then the universe will stop turning.

422
00:31:02,960 --> 00:31:08,520
It'll keen in a minor key.

423
00:31:08,520 --> 00:31:12,040
Aeolian tones
across the whole of creation.

424
00:31:12,840 --> 00:31:17,440
And that lament will be
my symphony supreme.

425
00:31:18,280 --> 00:31:20,160
With all of life extinguished.

426
00:31:21,240 --> 00:31:23,040
I'm goin' solo.

427
00:31:23,040 --> 00:31:24,880
How did you enter this world?

428
00:31:24,880 --> 00:31:28,760
Oh.
That would be telling, babe.

429
00:31:28,760 --> 00:31:30,600
No, babes!

430
00:31:30,600 --> 00:31:33,120
Your father established
the rules of fair play!

431
00:31:33,120 --> 00:31:35,920
One thing that he would never do is cheat.

432
00:31:36,800 --> 00:31:38,560
So I have a right to know.

433
00:31:39,960 --> 00:31:41,320
A genius.

434
00:31:41,960 --> 00:31:46,760
A single, silly man
who found the lost chord.

435
00:31:49,640 --> 00:31:52,760
Which means a different combination
of notes would banish you?

436
00:31:52,760 --> 00:31:56,040
I said, "Genius".

437
00:31:56,720 --> 00:31:59,480
And you might be bright.

438
00:32:00,000 --> 00:32:01,160
And hot.

439
00:32:01,160 --> 00:32:03,760
- And...

440
00:32:03,760 --> 00:32:05,200
..."timey wimey".

441
00:32:05,200 --> 00:32:08,280
But genius?

442
00:32:08,280 --> 00:32:10,080
Oh, honey, I don't think so.

443
00:32:13,080 --> 00:32:14,360
What are you doing?

444
00:32:14,360 --> 00:32:17,160
- Everything resonates, Doctor, dear.

445
00:32:17,160 --> 00:32:18,920
Every atom hums.

446
00:32:18,920 --> 00:32:23,400
And anything that plays a tune is mine.

447
00:32:25,200 --> 00:32:26,560
Sing along, Doctor.

448
00:32:28,880 --> 00:32:31,040
Everybody!

449
00:32:34,080 --> 00:32:37,040
What is it? What's hap--
- Maestro!

450
00:32:37,040 --> 00:32:39,080
Controlling the TARDIS.

451
00:32:39,080 --> 00:32:41,720
But I say never.

452
00:32:41,720 --> 00:32:43,320
Never!

453
00:32:44,200 --> 00:32:45,440
Ruby!

454
00:32:48,840 --> 00:32:50,600
- Are we flying?
- Only just.

455
00:32:52,160 --> 00:32:55,880
The only thing I can do
is take us back to 1963.

456
00:33:02,440 --> 00:33:06,560
- Where's Maestro?
- Composing.

457
00:33:06,560 --> 00:33:08,920
- And the next tune might be deadly.

458
00:33:08,920 --> 00:33:12,160
I'm sorry.

459
00:33:12,160 --> 00:33:14,320
I'm sorry, I'm sorry.

460
00:33:14,320 --> 00:33:15,680
Don't hate me.

461
00:33:20,080 --> 00:33:21,200
Okay, come on.

462
00:33:21,200 --> 00:33:22,760
Come on. Come on, come on, come on.

463
00:33:22,760 --> 00:33:24,440
Come on. Okay.

464
00:33:30,560 --> 00:33:31,960
Strange.

465
00:33:33,000 --> 00:33:34,800
- Did you break it?
- No.

466
00:33:36,000 --> 00:33:37,920
No, no, no, no, no. That's something else.

467
00:33:39,160 --> 00:33:42,440
- Okay.
- Right.

468
00:33:54,440 --> 00:33:58,720
Okay. If we can record the right tune on
the sonic, we can use this as a weapon.

469
00:33:58,720 --> 00:33:59,640
- Right.
- Yeah?

470
00:33:59,640 --> 00:34:01,160
- No, no, no, no.
- Oh. Oh, okay.

471
00:34:01,160 --> 00:34:03,240
We need to find the Notes of Banishment.

472
00:34:04,440 --> 00:34:07,000
Ah, John Lennon's guitar!

473
00:34:07,000 --> 00:34:08,720
That's gotta be a good start.

474
00:34:08,720 --> 00:34:09,920
Okay.

475
00:34:09,920 --> 00:34:12,320
- Okay, but don't you need to be a genius?
Uh--

476
00:34:12,320 --> 00:34:14,960
Oh, just-- No offence.
Just a musical genius.

477
00:34:14,960 --> 00:34:17,040
- Sometimes genius is just hard work.

478
00:34:17,040 --> 00:34:18,320
Yeah?

479
00:34:18,320 --> 00:34:20,600
If I can find the right notes.

480
00:34:22,160 --> 00:34:23,240
Wait a minute.

481
00:34:25,320 --> 00:34:28,960
There's 66 billion trillion
different tunes out there, but...

482
00:34:28,960 --> 00:34:30,200
No, but just wait.

483
00:34:31,480 --> 00:34:34,760
Can you hear that? That music?

484
00:34:39,000 --> 00:34:40,760
Whoa! No, no, no!

485
00:34:40,760 --> 00:34:41,720
Doctor!

486
00:34:41,720 --> 00:34:43,200
I thought that was non-diegetic.

487
00:34:43,200 --> 00:34:45,280
No, no, don't--

488
00:34:48,040 --> 00:34:49,520
Doctor!

489
00:34:49,520 --> 00:34:52,000
No, no, no, no, no, no,
no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no!

490
00:34:52,000 --> 00:34:54,000
No, no, no, no!

491
00:34:56,160 --> 00:35:00,480
Doctor!

492
00:35:00,480 --> 00:35:03,280
Wait! No, no, no, no!

493
00:35:13,640 --> 00:35:17,040
Put her down!

494
00:35:27,400 --> 00:35:30,400
Can't trick me twice, honey!

495
00:35:30,400 --> 00:35:32,560
- Then fight me!

496
00:35:32,560 --> 00:35:34,440
Huh? Leave her alone!

497
00:35:34,440 --> 00:35:41,280
But she's the only human left
with music in her heart!

498
00:35:43,800 --> 00:35:49,520
Playing lovesick songs
for heartbroken lesbians,

499
00:35:49,520 --> 00:35:53,800
and that just makes me hungry

500
00:35:54,400 --> 00:35:56,760
for all those delicious songs.

501
00:35:56,760 --> 00:35:59,880
Let me go!

502
00:36:01,400 --> 00:36:05,160
- That's right, pretty girl! Sing!

503
00:36:10,240 --> 00:36:11,560
Maestro.

504
00:36:11,560 --> 00:36:14,760
- Maestro, I am asking you. Just--

505
00:36:16,960 --> 00:36:18,160
What?

506
00:36:22,720 --> 00:36:23,960
That's wrong.

507
00:36:23,960 --> 00:36:25,720
What do you mean?

508
00:36:25,720 --> 00:36:30,440
There's a hidden song
deep inside her soul.

509
00:36:30,440 --> 00:36:31,880
- What is it?

510
00:36:33,960 --> 00:36:35,480
What?

511
00:36:36,440 --> 00:36:38,040
Ruby.

512
00:36:44,160 --> 00:36:46,080
What is this?

513
00:36:47,080 --> 00:36:48,640
Christmas.

514
00:36:49,360 --> 00:36:51,760
The music that was playing
the night that she was born.

515
00:36:54,800 --> 00:36:57,640
How could a song have so much power?

516
00:36:58,440 --> 00:36:59,960
And power like him?

517
00:36:59,960 --> 00:37:01,840
- Like who?
- The oldest one.

518
00:37:01,840 --> 00:37:05,360
On the night of her birth,
he can't have been there.

519
00:37:05,360 --> 00:37:07,520
- What for?

520
00:37:08,080 --> 00:37:11,280
- What for? What for? What for?
Who was there?

521
00:37:15,360 --> 00:37:17,240
Enough.

522
00:37:18,320 --> 00:37:21,920
- Whoa!

523
00:37:21,920 --> 00:37:23,200
- You okay?
- Yeah, yeah.

524
00:37:23,200 --> 00:37:25,320
- I've got you. I've got you.
- Okay, okay.

525
00:37:25,320 --> 00:37:29,000
What was it? What happened?
- It's all right. All right? It's okay.

526
00:37:30,120 --> 00:37:33,320
This creature is very wrong.

527
00:37:33,320 --> 00:37:39,720
And this-- this is very, very, very right.

528
00:37:41,560 --> 00:37:43,280
Do you know what this is?

529
00:37:44,480 --> 00:37:46,720
This is the famous Abbey Road piano.

530
00:37:48,280 --> 00:37:51,320
They call it the Mrs Mills Piano.

531
00:37:51,320 --> 00:37:52,800
Oho!

532
00:37:52,800 --> 00:37:53,880
Oh, she was a girl.

